        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>With the current sensitivity and angular resolution, given the position of the source, 
the ALMA array is unique in its ability to detect 
the extent of outflows from ISO-Oph 102.
 
As our main goal is to detect the extent of outflows from ISO-Oph 102 and
the 12CO J=2-1 outflows from the source have been detected (Phan-Bao et al. 2008), 
we therefore use band 6 (230 GHz) to explore the extent of the 12CO J=2-1 outflows from the target.

Our SMA observations with a spectral resolution of 
0.27 km/s were able to resolve the outflows
from the target. We therefore use bandwidth of 234 MHz, giving 
a spectral resolution of 0.122 MHz or 0.16 km/s (smoothed) for ALMA. The 3 remaining basebands are configured with bandwidth of 2 GHz for continuum.

The SMA compact configuration with a synthezised beam of 3.6"x2.4" was able
to spatially resolve the outflow components, 
the most compact 12m configuration with a resolution of about 1.6" is certainly able to 
resolve the outflows from the source. 
If the outflows from ISO-Oph 102 is episodic, the knot-like outflow features will be observable.
These features may extend to a distance of 12" (or 3150 AU) for the case of ESO-Halpha 574
(a young low-mass star, Comeron &amp; Reipurth 2006) or 16" (or 720 AU) for the case of 2MASS J1207 
(a young brown dwarf of 24 Jupiter mass, Whelan et al. 2012).
For the first attempt of exploring the extent
of outflows from ISO-Oph 102 (60 Jupiter mass), 
we therefore extend the map to a distance of 30"
(or 3750 AU at 125 pc) from the central object, which is reasonble for an outflow of 
the brown dwarf with a mass between ESO-Halpha 574 and 2MASS J1207.
This requires 9 pointings to fully cover the requested region.
As the largest angular structure in source is about 15" (see Figure 1), which exceeds
the maximum recoverable scale of 11.3" offered by the 12m array, 
we therefore need ACA for these observations.

As the flux of knot-like outflow features of the source is not known and
no brown dwarf reference with detected knot-like molecular outflow features  
has been available so far. 
So, we estimate the sensitivity to detect the faint features around the central object, e.g.,
the gas lobe around the central position of ISO-Oph 102 (see Figure 1).
The faint gas lobe was detected by SMA at only 3 sigma, resulting in a flux of 0.45 Jy/beam
(SMA beam of 3.6"x2.4"), we then derive a flux of 0.13 Jy/beam (ALMA beam of 1.6"x1.6")
for the ALMA 12m array. To detect the gas lobe at 5 sigma, 
we need a sensitivity 0.026 Jy/beam or 26 mJy/beam.

The sensitivity of 26 mJy/beam requests a total time on source of 6.1 min for 9 pointings of the 12m array.
Including calibration and overheads, the total 12m array time to carry out this project is 32.4 min or 0.54 h.
The total ACA time is 2.16 h. Therefore, we need a total time for science goal is 2.7 h.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
