    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Brown dwarfs are on the dividing line between planets and stars. Up to date, about 1,000 brown dwarfs, including the coolest known brown dwarfs with temperatures of ~300 K as cool as the human body, have been discovered. Observations of brown dwarfs properties in different star-forming regions have demonstrated that these statistical properties of brown dwarfs appear to form a continuum with those of low-mass stars. This strongly supports the scenario that brown dwarfs form as a scaled-down version of low-mass stars. However, it is still unclear how the physical processes of brown dwarf formation occur. Our SMA observations of molecular outflows from brown dwarfs in rho Ophiuchi and Taurus suggest that the outflow process in brown dwarfs could be episodic. In this proposal, we propose to explore the extent of outflows from the young brown dwarf ISO-Oph 102 in rho Ophiuchi with ALMA to confirm whether the outflow process is episodic. This may provide an important implication for brown dwarf formation mechanism.
</prp:abstract>
